03087nam a22004335i 9780804768115DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222007cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047681157 a10.1515/97808047681152doi  a(DE-B1597)581876  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aLIT0060002bisacsh1 aSzafraniec, Asja, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBeckett, Derrida, and the Event of Literature /cAsja Szafraniec. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCultural Memory in the Present00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Question of Literature -- t2. A Singular Odyssey -- t3. Beckett, Derrida, and the Ordinary -- t4. Beckett's "Exhausted" Archives -- t5. Singular Points of Transaction (I): The Subject -- t6. Singular Points of Transaction (II): "What Are Poets For?" The Authority of Literature -- t7. Singular Points of Transaction (III): "Wanting in Inanity." Negativity, Language, and "God" in Beckett -- tConcluding Remarks -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tCultural Memory in the Present0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe late Jacques Derrida’s notion of literature is explored in this new study. Starting with Derrida’s self-professed inability to comment on the work of Samuel Beckett, whom Derrida nevertheless considered one of the most interesting and exemplary writers of our time, Asja Szafraniec argues that the shared feature of literary works as Derrida understands them is a double, juridical-economical gesture, and that one aspect of this notion (the juridical) is more hospitable to Beckett’s oeuvre than the other. She then discusses other contemporary philosophical approaches to Beckett, including those of Gilles Deleuze, Stanley Cavell, and Alain Badiou. The book offers an innovative analysis of Derrida’s approach to literature, as well as an overview of current philosophical approaches to contemporary literature, and a number of innovative readings of Beckett’s work.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476811540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804768115423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804768115/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles